Lecture 0: Introduction to Jupyter Notebook and Python ¶

@prepared by Hoang Duc Thuong, Department of Space and Applications, USTH. hoang-duc.thuong@usth.edu.vn

Data Science is a branch of computer science where we study how to store, use and analyze data for deriving information. In this lecture, I will provide practices on:

  • JupyterLab which is the development of Jupyter Notebook. JupyterLab is a flexible interactive web-based environtment for Python programme and visualization.
  • Python and scientific computing which is the center of the lecture. I will introduce Python programming language, then I will provide overview of some useful libraries in scientific analysis and visualization: NumPy, Matplotlib, Scipy, Astropy.

I also present the combination of Jupyter notebook and Hypertext Markup Language(HTML) to build this web-based lecture note.

1. JupyterLab ¶

It is an interactive web-based coding editor compare to Visual studio, Sublime, Atom, Aquamac, emacs, vim, Spyder. It likes a living Ipython environment.

1.1. General ¶

Let's start JupyterLab form a Mac OS terminal. It is similar in a Linux system. We can start JupyterLab via Anaconda on a Windows computer.

  • Shift + Enter to run a cell.
  • Raw: Normal text format.
  • Code cells: Edit and write code, the programming language will define the kernel
  • Markdown: Documentation in a literature way, this is used to organized the structure of the document. We can also write mathematics using LaTex formalism.

Mathermatics:¶

Create equations using Latex $$y=ax^2 + bx +c$$ $$ \partial f = \frac{dy}{dx}. $$

$$P(A \mid B) = \frac{P(B \mid A)P(A)}{P(B)}. $$

or math expressions:
Maxell equations \begin{equation} t = \sqrt{x^2 + y^2 + z^2}. \end{equation}

\begin{align} \nabla = \frac{\partial}{\partial x} + \frac{\partial}{\partial y} + \frac{\partial}{\partial z}. \end{align}\begin{align} \nabla \times \vec{\mathbf{B}} -\, \frac1c\, \frac{\partial\vec{\mathbf{E}}}{\partial t} & = \frac{4\pi}{c}\vec{\mathbf{j}}. \\ \nabla \cdot \vec{\mathbf{E}} & = 4 \pi \rho. \\ \nabla \times \vec{\mathbf{E}}\, +\, \frac1c\, \frac{\partial\vec{\mathbf{B}}}{\partial t} & = \vec{\mathbf{0}}. \\ \nabla \cdot \vec{\mathbf{B}} & = 0. \end{align}
  • Uniform distribution \begin{align} \text{Probability density function:} \\ \begin{cases} \frac{1}{b-a}&\text{for $x\in[a,b]$} \\ 0&\text{otherwise} \\ \end{cases} \\ \text{Cumulative distribution function:} \\ \begin{cases} 0&\text{for $x<a$} \\ \frac{x-a}{b-a}&\text{for $x\in[a,b)$} \\ 1&\text{for $x\ge b$} \\ \end{cases} \end{align}

Live plot¶

This is the powerful function of Notebook that helps to quick debug and living output.

In [4]:
#%config InlineBackend.figure_format ='retina'
import matplotlib.pylab as plt

x = range(1000)
y = [i ** 2 for i in x]

plt.plot(x,y)
plt.show()

Cell magic : Make a new file, view, run¶

Cell magics are the system of command conventions.

%lsmagic : List all avalable magics.
%matplotlib inline : All plot in the frame of the jupyterLab, important
%timeit : Caculate the time execution of code
%%writefile : This is a very useful command to write the cell contents.
%%script : Run the script with argument.
%%latex : Latex type.
%%html : HTML.
%%javascript : Java script.
%pwd : Print current working directory.
%load : Insert code from external script.
%run : Excute python code.
...

Presentation slideshow (Jupyterlab extention)¶

  • We can creating presentations with Jupyter Notebook:
    jupyter nbconvert Lec0_Intro_Notebook_and_Python.ipynb --to slides --post serve. This command will create an .html file that can display as presentation.
  • RISE plugin can make a live slidesshows on Jupyter Notebook
